{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1745"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.3,0.45,0.04,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109442"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91807"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"907"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109442"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 30-minute history of shortness of breath and a sensation of her heart racing. She denies any chest pain or tightness and reports that this came on suddenly while having breakfast. She has never experienced an episode like this before. On further questioning, she reveals that she had a cup of coffee this morning as she was running late, while she usually consumes only tea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is alert and orientated. Her heart rate is 140/min, blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, SpO2 is 99%, and respiratory rate is 20/min. Examination of the cardiovascular and respiratory systems is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Supraventricular tachycardia","Sinus tachycardia","Atrial tachycardia","Atrial flutter"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esinus tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by a heart rate greater than 100 beats per minute with a normal P wave preceding each QRS complex. In sinus tachycardia, the rhythm is regular, and the P waves are typically upright in leads I, II, and aVF, indicating that the impulse originates from the sinoatrial node. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraventricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E (SVT) is a broad term that encompasses any tachycardia originating above the ventricles. It often presents with a rapid heart rate and narrow QRS complexes, but the P waves may be absent, inverted, or occur after the QRS complex, depending on the type of SVT. In contrast, sinus tachycardia maintains a normal P wave morphology and sequence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by an irregularly irregular rhythm with no distinct P waves, which is not observed in this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial flutter\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a \u0027sawtooth\u0027 pattern of flutter waves, which are absent here. \u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E may show abnormal P wave morphology, but this patient\u0027s ECG shows normal P waves, ruling out this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient\u0027s recent caffeine intake could be a physiological trigger for sinus tachycardia. Identifying and addressing the underlying cause is crucial in managing sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sinus tachycardia may be pathological or physiological in nature and identification of the cause is the cornerstone of management."],"references":["Henning A, Krawiec C. Sinus Tachycardia. [Updated 2021 Jun 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553128/","Mayuga KA, Fedorowski A, Ricci F, Gopinathannair R, Dukes JW, Gibbons C, Hanna P, Sorajja D, Chung M, Benditt D, Sheldon R, Ayache MB, AbouAssi H, Shivkumar K, Grubb BP, Hamdan MH, Stavrakis S, Singh T, Goldberger JJ, Muldowney JAS 3rd, Belham M, Kem DC, Akin C, Bruce BK, Zahka NE, Fu Q, Van Iterson EH, Raj SR, Fouad-Tarazi F, Goldstein DS, Stewart J, Olshansky B. Sinus Tachycardia: a Multidisciplinary Expert Focused Review. Circ Arrhythm Electrophysiol. 2022 Sep;15(9):e007960. doi: 10.1161/CIRCEP.121.007960. Epub 2022 Sep 8. PMID: 36074973; PMCID: PMC9523592. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36074973/","Gopinathannair R, Olshansky B. Management of tachycardia. F1000Prime Rep. 2015 May 12;7:60. doi: 10.12703/P7-60. PMID: 26097733; PMCID: PMC4447058. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4447058/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91807"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19193"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19193"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/900212b9-b101-4f2d-ac13-a89174248993.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/900212b9-b101-4f2d-ac13-a89174248993.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":414}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91807"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T11:38:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T11:38:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1745"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109442"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty